Farmers are allowed to start annual kink maintenance on Monday
Schleswig-Holstein's farmers are allowed to start annual kink maintenance on Monday.
The "green ramparts", which are unique in Germany, have shaped the landscape of the forest-poor federal state for around 200 years.
The tree and scrubs up to five meters wide are "forest replacement" and for many animals and plants the last retreats.
Knicks connect as corridors scattered habitats, over which the exchange of organisms can still function, as the managing director of the Naturschutzbund Deutschland (NABU) in Schleswig-Holstein, Ingo Ludwichowski, said.
Knicks are living fences
The Knicks were laid out on the basis of an order of the Danish King Christian VI in 1766, who ruled over Schleswig-Holstein.
The "living fences" were not only field boundary and cattle fence, they also provided the farmers with firewood and beams for their half-timbered houses.
From that time also his name "Knick" comes: By "bucking" of the branches, the dense, intertwined boundaries could develop.
Today, around 45 000 kilometres of hedges stretch between the North Sea and the Baltic Sea, giving the image to a wood-rich, diversely structured landscape.
