This is how Schalke's naldo "great sport" succeeds on the bench
For the third time in a row not in the starting eleven: Nevertheless, Naldo thanks Schalke coach Domenico Tedesco.
Gelsenkirchen - After Ronaldo Aparecido Rodrigues had not sat in the Schalker starting eleven for the third time in a row, but on the exchange bench, the understanding would have been great for many people if the almost two-meter-tall Brazilian had really talked about the frustration of the soul.
But when the Schalker players gathered in the middle circle as usual after the 1:0 victory over FSV Mainz 05 and thanks head coach Domenico Tedesco to all his pros, the 36-year-old, whom everyone calls Naldo, turned on and said; "We have to thank, coach!"
"That was very emotional, that was great sport," Tedesco later said of the reaction of his vice-captain, who did not hold any grudges despite his renewed reservist existence.
Vorscheinlích knows Naldo, who was celebrated as the best Schalker last season, that he has actually not fallen on the siding of his coach - but is given a break for good reasons.
A reason called "load control."
It was not easy to tell him that
"It wasn't easy to tell him that, I'm telling you quite honestly," Tedesco reported from the moment he told Naldo that he was not in the starting eleven.
He's an important player, he's an important person.
But it's always about the matter, it's about the club," Tedesco justified the move.
Naldo played 90 minutes against Bayern and Porto.
He is 36 years old.
It is important that everyone can take a breather at the moment.
And that we all keep in the boat," Tedesco explained of the rotation, which has also recently caught Naldo.
And to which the Brazilian reacted with the wisdom of his advanced age: by also turning out to be an exemplary team player on the bench.
The mood in Austria's industry accelerated in August compared to the eurozone.
The Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) was at a 37-month low at 46.7 points.
Austria is still the third best mood behind Ireland and the Netherlands, the Markit Institute said on Monday in its survey of 3,000 companies.
Unlike in Austria, the PMI of the euro zone rose by 1.1 to 45.1 points, the index is still the 13th. Month in a row below the mark of 50 counters, which indicates growth.
Only Ireland's industry cracked that threshold in August with 50.9 points.
The bottom line was the Greeks (42.1 points).
In Germany, France and Spain, the mood barometer fell, but more slowly than in the months before.
In Spain, the index hit its highest level since March, at 44.0 points.
"The slightly weakened downturn could mean that the worst is over," said Markit economist Rob Dobson.
But the industry - in the third quarter anyway - remains the number one growth brake.
A rapid return to the growth zone is not in sight: export orders in the eurozone fell as sharply as they have not since November 2011.
The companies therefore cut jobs for the seventh consecutive month.
In China, too, industrial production fell more sharply in August than initially thought.
The mood barometer fell to 47.6 points from 49.3 points the previous month.
Experts had initially expected 47.8 points.
The Purchasing Managers Index bases its figures on representative surveys of 3,000 European industrial companies.
Among other things, developments in sales, employment, warehouses and prices are collected.
